Spikes.

A spike is a floor trap that wounds the player for as long as they stand on it. Where a hazard costs the player a whole life on contact, a spike instead grinds away at their health a bite at a time, dealing its attack damage over and over on a timer until they step off. A shield can soak the hits, and a spike can be made destroyable so a player with enough firepower can break it rather than endure it. Spikes come in a single-tile form and a ranged area that fills a whole rectangle with the same trap.

How a spike works.

A spike fills a single tile or a rectangular area and loops its spike sound from that spot. While the player stands anywhere inside it, every interval the spike strikes: it plays its hit clip and takes a chunk out of the player's health, lessened by the player's defence but never reduced to nothing. Stepping off stops the hits, and stepping back on resumes them. If the player has a shield up, the shield takes the damage instead of their health, wearing the shield down rather than them.

A spike carries its own health and a destroyable switch. When destroyable, enough incoming damage — from an explosive or another trap — drops the spike's health to zero, at which point it plays its death clip and disappears. A spike that isn't destroyable simply endures and keeps striking. On 3d maps a ranged spike fills every height level between its minimum and maximum z.

Spike fields.

The spike form takes the following:

Build mode. Single for one exact tile, or ranged for a rectangular area. Single is the default.

Coordinates. For a single spike, an x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the one tile it sits on. For a ranged spike, a minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangle it fills.

Health. How much damage the spike can absorb before it's destroyed, used only when destroyable is on.

Maximum attack. The damage the spike deals to the player on each strike, before the player's defence is subtracted.

Speed. The number of milliseconds between each strike while the player stands on the spike, so a smaller number hurts faster.

Spike sound (a folder name from the spike sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the idle loop, the hit clip struck on each tick, and the death clip when the spike is destroyed. Pick none for a silent spike.

Destroyable (checkbox). When checked, the spike can be broken by enough incoming damage; when unchecked, it can't be destroyed.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the spike sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the highlighted theme's hit clip, hold control and press L to hear its idle loop, and hold control and press H to hear its death clip.

Authoring spikes by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a spike is written under the name spike. A single one is spike x y health damage speed spiketype destroyable, and on 3d maps a z follows the y: spike x y z health damage speed spiketype destroyable. A ranged one is spike minx maxx miny maxy health damage speed spiketype destroyable, and on 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: spike minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz health damage speed spiketype destroyable. Both forms share the one spike name — the line is read as ranged when it carries the extra coordinates. The destroyable field is the literal word true or false, and the spike sound must match a spike sounds folder name or the word none.
